drawing-database-api — a first-class CL drawing value, and the four surfaces over it
====================================================================================

Parent tracking issue. Roadmap: implementation-roadmap.org
"Phase 17 — Drawing Database, Persistence, and Multi-Document"
(sub-phases 17a..17h).

Break-out issues:
  drawing-codec-libredwg-submodule.issue              (Phase 17e decision)
  deferred-document-lifecycle-command-semantics.issue (Phase 17f parity)

See also:
  clautolisp/autolisp-mock-host/source/model.lisp  (today's host == one drawing)
  clautolisp/autolisp-mock-host/source/entity-api.lisp
  clautolisp/autolisp-host/source/protocol.lisp    (host-command, host-vlax-*)
  clautolisp/autolisp-mock-host/source/com-progids.lisp (AutoCAD.Document stub)

Context
-------

clautolisp can run AutoLISP against an in-memory CAD substrate,
but that substrate is welded to the host. `mock-host` holds the
entity table, creation-order, symbol tables, named-object
dictionary and sysvars directly in its own slots — so *the host
IS a single drawing*. There is no way to:

  - open a drawing from a file (no DXF/DWG codec exists anywhere),
  - enumerate / introspect / mutate a drawing as plain data,
  - hold more than one drawing at a time.

The motivating use cases are headless Common-Lisp tools, not
AutoLISP programs:

  - `identify-drawing foo.dwg` — characterise a drawing as
    SCHMS / SCHMS+ / SCHME / SCHMIEU / SCHSME+ (and version) from
    its entity attributes + drawing-wide metadata.
  - `extract-schms-data foo.dwg -o foo.json` — process a drawing
    and export its SCHMS+ payload, from a CLI, no GUI boot.

These want a documented CL API; AutoLISP is optional sugar on top.

The four surfaces, and why they are layered (not parallel)
----------------------------------------------------------

A drawing is reachable four ways. The crucial design call is that
the Common-Lisp API is the *base*, and the three AutoLISP-facing
surfaces are veneers over it:

  1. Active-drawing entity API — the documented AutoLISP entity
     functions (entget / entmod / entmake / ssget / tblsearch /
     getvar / …). They see only the drawing the running LISP image
     lives in. After the 17a refactor they run against
     `(active-drawing host)` with no AutoLISP-visible change.

  2. NEW / OPEN / SAVE / CLOSE — the AutoCAD command system, run
     through `host-command`. Each command brings its own AutoLISP
     image/context along. These do NOT resume the calling routine
     inline (real AutoCAD defers the document switch) — see the
     break-out parity issue.

  3. COM / ObjectDBX (`AxDbDocument`) — the out-of-namespace,
     headless way an AutoLISP programmer opens *another* drawing
     and walks it by COM iteration. Side documents are invisible
     to entget / ssget.

  4. The Common-Lisp drawing API — create / load / introspect /
     modify / save / close a drawing and its namespace. Public and
     formally specified. The implementations of (1), (2) and (3)
     are all written against it.

Why this isn't already done
---------------------------

The work was implicit in the host design but never separated out,
and it carries three real decisions:

  - **Codec.** DWG is proprietary, binary, version-stamped, with
    no Autodesk spec. DXF is documented and maps ~1:1 onto the
    group-code lists already stored. So DXF first (no deps), DWG
    via libredwg later. (Break-out issue.)
  - **Command semantics.** `(command "_.OPEN" …)` cannot drive the
    document lifecycle and then continue the routine in real
    AutoCAD. clautolisp must either model the deferred switch or
    pick and document a divergence. (Break-out parity issue.)
  - **Refactor risk.** Pulling the drawing out of `mock-host`
    touches the whole backend. It is gated on the existing suite
    staying green (Phase 17a acceptance).

In scope
--------

  1. Phase 17a — extract a `clautolisp.drawing` value object;
     rewrite `mock-host` to hold one drawing and delegate. No
     AutoLISP-visible change; existing suite green is the gate.

  2. Phase 17b — the public, documented, exported CL API:
     read-drawing / write-drawing; map-entities / do-entities,
     find-entity, entity-dxf, entity-kind, drawing-sysvar,
     drawing-tables, table-records, drawing-dictionary;
     add-entity / modify-entity / delete-entity / set-sysvar and
     table/dict mutators. Pure CL values — no autolisp-runtime
     wrapper types leak into this layer.

  3. Phase 17c — `clautolisp.drawing.dxf`: pure-CL DXF reader +
     writer over the API, with round-trip + snapshot tests.

  4. Phase 17d — the CL tools (identify-drawing,
     extract-schms-data) as proof the API is self-sufficient.

  5. Phase 17e — libredwg submodule + DWG codec. (Break-out.)

  6. Phase 17f — multi-document host + NEW/OPEN/SAVE/CLOSE +
     per-document contexts + the drawing argument (clautolisp and
     alfe). (Parity break-out.)

  7. Phase 17g — ObjectDBX/COM veneer (`AxDbDocument`), side
     documents invisible to entget/ssget.

  8. Phase 17h — blackboard (vl-bb-set / vl-bb-ref) + global
     namespace for cross-drawing transport.

Out of scope
------------

  - A DWG codec written from scratch — we use libredwg.
  - vl-file-* changes — byte/path level, deliberately separate
    from the codec; it never parses a drawing.
  - Concurrent multi-session execution beyond what runtime-session
    already isolates (tracked under Open Architectural Questions).

Acceptance criteria
-------------------

  - 17a: full existing suite passes with the drawing extracted;
    no AutoLISP-visible behaviour differs.
  - 17b: the CL API is exported and documented in a
    *-specifications.org, with unit tests independent of any
    AutoLISP program.
  - 17c: a fixture drawing round-trips load -> write -> load with
    entity/table/sysvar fidelity.
  - 17d: `identify-drawing` classifies a corpus of real
    SCHMS-family fixtures correctly, driven purely by the CL API.
  - Conventions: DEVELOP bumped on each source-touching step;
    AutoLISP-visible extensions take the `clal-` prefix; the
    NEW/OPEN/CLOSE divergence carries a parity issue.
